        "transcriptMarkdown": "# 34. Day 2 Questions: Biodynamic Embryology and the Human Body\n\n## Brain Movement: Foundation of Cranial Osteopathy\n\n**Brain developmental movement** is fundamental and provides deep meaning in **cranial osteopathy**. The human body is intrinsically intelligent and knows the paths of its own development.\n\nOur role is not to re-educate the brain, but to learn to listen to it. It will instruct and guide us.\n\nWe will learn to \"do the **brain's Tai Chi**\", observing that the **base of the skull** is intimately linked to the brain. The **ventricular system** and the **deep flow of the brain** depend on its dynamics.\n\nSimilarly, the entire **membranous system** (tension membranes, falx cerebri, tentorium cerebelli, falx cerebelli, dural membranes, parietal, visceral) depends on brain dynamics. This compartmentalisation of the brain, from the dense structure of the cranial base to the vault, reflects these dynamics.\n\n## The Viscerocranium and Organic Connections\n\nWe will study the **viscerocranium**, starting with the **transverse septum**. This is a tissue integration including the heart, the diaphragm, and extending with the **falciform ligament**.\n\nThis structure reveals an early functional integration between the heart and the liver. It continues via the **foramen of Winslow** to form the **greater omentum**.\n\n### Implicit Relationships\n\nThis means there is a fundamental relationship between:\n\n- **The heart**\n- **The diaphragm**\n- **The brain**\n- **The immune system**\n\nDestabilisation at the heart or base of the skull can therefore impact the immune system. The superior immune system, **Waldeyer-Heiner's ring** (tonsils), is an example of this.\n\n### Impact on the ENT Sphere\n\nDysfunction at this level can have significant repercussions. For example, many children suffering from **ENT** problems show, at a molecular level, the same **immunoglobulin** (type 1) as that found in the caecum.\n\nDestabilisation of the **peritoneum** can thus affect the entire ENT sphere. In practice, rebalancing the ENT sphere often requires rebalancing the peritoneum, particularly at the caecal level, which contains lymphatic tissues identical to those of the tonsils. It is interesting to note that in the past, tonsillectomies and appendectomies were often performed synchronously.\n\n## The Oesophagus and its Interconnections\n\nThe oesophageal relationship is also crucial. The **oesophageal mesenchyme** can disrupt diaphragm function.\n\nThe stomach and oesophagus are suspended to the base of the skull via the **carotid foramina**, the **pterygoid plexuses**, and the **pterygoids**. Any destabilisation of the base of the skull can therefore alter **cardio-tuberosity** function and, consequently, diaphragmatic movement, which is essential for our physiology.\n\n### The Mesoblastic Wall and the Diaphragm\n\nThe **lateral mesoblastic wall** (lateral wall) is also very important. The **rib cage** is entirely dependent on the proper functioning of the diaphragm.\n\nConsequently, the entire dorsal area is linked to these dynamics. Furthermore, we have noted a junction with the **kidney**, the **psoas**, and the **duodenum**, highlighting the overall integrity of the system.\n\n### The Importance of the Diaphragm\n\nWe must learn to work the diaphragm with more subtlety, whether at a distance or not. By expanding this diaphragm, the patient's quality of life is significantly improved.\n\nWhen exercising the diaphragm, an essential reference point is its **fulcrum**. It is possible to suspend this fulcrum in the dynamic immobility of space.\n\nIt's like a door that opens and closes, with a hinge, a **\"Hitchpoint\"** or fulcrum. This starting point may seem mobile, but on closer inspection, it becomes a fixed point, your reference, but always suspended in the dynamic immobility of the system.\n\n## The Heart, Peritoneum, and Embryonic Movements\n\nA question arises regarding the **meso-oesophagus** and the **vena cava**. This is very close to the heart, almost in the same axis, and not far from the liver.\n\nThe first major movement of the **notochord** and the second, circular, movement of the **amniotic cavity** involve a visceral centre that we identify with the heart and peritoneum.\n\n### The Image of Coiling\n\nThe image is one of **coiling** around the **cardio-pleuro-peritoneal** system, like a joint. The **neural tube** develops strongly forwards, drawing the heart, but it also grows backwards, bringing the allantois through an anterior restriction field.\n\nThis means there is a movement of body closure by the **embryonic pedicle**. It is at this point that the allantois and the heart integrate, becoming a fulcrum.\n\n### The Origin of the Transverse Septum\n\nAt this stage, two elements are crucial: the heart pushing on the southern part and the upper part of the **vitelline vesicle**. This push guides and organises the **transverse septum**.\n\nIts tissue origin was already present (the cells were there), but this encounter between the brain and the heart, and the heart and the vitelline vesicle, provides the impetus for the creation of the transverse septum. The heart thus acts as a joint between the brain and the diaphragm."
