        "title": "9- The Heart_Dynamics of Developmental Movement",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# The Heart: Dynamics of Developmental Movement\n\n## Introduction to Embryonic Cardiac Development\n\nWe will observe the **exponential growth** and **folding** of the embryo.\n\nHere, we only see the **vitelline cavity**. Above it, the **amniotic cavity** has been cut.\n\nThere is **longitudinal growth** and **flexion**. We can distinguish the **nervous system**, the **somites**, and the **vascular systems**.\n\nLet's focus on an opening, the **future opening of the intraembryonic coelom**. We must imagine it here. It will later transform this external coelom into an internal coelom.\n\nThe impressive growth of the system brings the two **primitive endocardial tubes** closer to the midline, due to a **differential growth rate**, influenced by the **notochord**.\n\nThis approximation of the endocardial tubes forms the **intestine** above, and all around, the **intraembryonic cavity**. At this stage, this will form the **pericardial cavity**, not the peritoneal cavity.\n\nThe **vitelline vesicle** moves closer to form the upper part of the intestine.\n\n## Key Movements of Cardiac Development\n\nThe approximation of the two endocardial tubes forms the area of the developing **cardiac tube**.\n\nWe observe a movement of approximation towards the midline and, simultaneously, a movement where the brain \"does that\". It's a combination of both.\n\nThis process is synchronous with the **flexion** phase of the embryo. The meeting of the thumbs symbolises this first movement at the heart level.\n\n### The Heart's \"Looping\" Movement\n\nThe heart, in sagittal view, meets and seeks to develop. It lacks space behind it, and little space to the left or right. It only has space forwards.\n\nWithin the heart itself, it will find its own **fulcrum**. With the back blocked, it develops forwards, performing what is called the heart's **\"looping\" movement**. This is phase 2.\n\nThis continuous development forms a third level. The space between the **ventricular system** and the **atrium** becomes a pivot point. The ventricle, initially above, ends up below relative to the system. This is an **inversion** movement.\n\nHere are the three main movements:\n\n1.  **Approximation** towards the midline and meeting.\n2.  **\"Looping\" movement** forwards.\n3.  **Inversion process** of the ventricle.\n\n### The Influence of the Peritoneal Cavity and Symmetry Breaking\n\nThe third movement is linked to the inversion process, which is a developmental process of the **peritoneal cavity**.\n\nThe development of the **liver** causes a shift in movement. The lesser sac displaces the left main bronchus higher than the right, linked to the **breaking of axial symmetry**.\n\nWe therefore observe a movement of development forwards, but also to the left. This is a **double tilt**.\n\nLet's mainly remember:\n\n*   The heart's **approximation** towards the midline.\n*   **Development** forwards.\n*   Simultaneous development to the left.\n\nThe liver's **sinusoidal system** will position itself upwards after this tilt.\n\n### Organisation of the Great Vessels\n\nThe first movement, then the second movement linked to the tilt, and finally a third movement that organises the **great vessels** above.\n\nThe heart is tilted, held by an axis, and balanced relative to the **vascular plane**. There is greater development on one side.\n\nIt is a balance between the **thoracic** part, the **abdominal** part, and the **low visceral** part. A very important movement occurs between the heart, stomach, and liver.\n\n## The Embryonic Imprint in a Biodynamic Approach\n\nA very important reference point to rebalance is the **hepatic movement**. We observe whether the liver is well in its developmental movement or if it is receding.\n\nIf the liver stops, there is a small halt.\n\nAt the heart level, its development will do the opposite. There is a trajectory, like an **imprint**.\n\nOne must position oneself on the embryonic imprint, go where the system wishes to go; that is where the **still point** is.\n\nIf the movement does not go far enough, the system must be helped. This organisation of the heart is strongly influenced by the liver. Hence the importance of understanding the liver's role.\n\nIn biodynamic embryology, we do not impose. We reject neither **fascial restrictions**, nor the **fluid** aspect, nor **structural**, **visceral** or other techniques.\n\nThe approach is to adapt to what is felt in the present moment. The therapeutic force lies in the meeting of the two neutrals.\n\nRegeneration processes in **biodynamic osteopathy** use these embryonic movements. It is not direct therapy, but rather recognising the embryonic developmental movements that appear in therapeutic processes guided by the **\"tide\"**.\n\nIt is crucial to recognise the frequency one is on.\n\n## The Heart's Energy and Its Environment\n\nWe rarely touch the heart directly first. The heart forms by the **echo** from the periphery.\n\nThe heart is extremely powerful because it receives very important information from the **neural crest**. It receives even more powerful electrical information on a neurological level.\n\nThis means that one can learn to feel the heart at a distance, or that the heart is felt at a distance. It has a power, a **radiance**. Measurements have shown a radiance up to a minimum of 5 metres from the person, probably linked to the neural crest.\n\nIt is on the **venous** plane that there will be development, called the **venous sinus** of the heart. In this venous sinus, the **cardinal veins**, **umbilical veins**, and **vitelline veins** will converge, undergoing many remodelling processes.\n\nThe heart has a **fascial** environment and its own **electricity** for its beat. However, this electricity was not enough to maintain the heart in its proper function. It depends heavily on its entire fascial environment.\n\nThe **sterno-pericardial**, **phrenico-pericardial**, **vertebro-pericardial ligaments**, and the **superior aorta**, suspended up to the pharyngeal tubercle, support the heart's **rhythmicity**.\n\nThe heart's attachment system is a **closed oscillation system**. Its tissue and molecular structure is designed to undergo a stretching movement with each beat. It's like a system of **elastic bands** that constantly bring the heart back to its equilibrium position.\n\nThis structuring of the pericardium's **tissue fascia** supports the heart, and the heart itself is supported in its rhythmicity by its fascial environment.\n\nThe entire fascial system around the heart can influence its rhythm. Hence the importance of the **structural freedom** of the cardiac environment. This is where direct action is possible.\n\nThe heart in **systole-diastole** should be seen as an **octopus**, with the **aortic arch** and the entire descending trunk down to the junctions.\n\nIt's not just the body, but also its \"tentacles\" that can be felt. In the belly, in the throat, in the feet, in the fingers.\n\nThis implies that a **destabilisation** of the hip can destabilise the heart. There are cases of **arrhythmias** that can be improved by freeing the hips.\n\nThere is a complex relationship through the **endothelium**, this tissue that connects the entire system."
