        "title": "11- The Heart_Development of Arterial Anatomy",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# The Heart: Development of Arterial Anatomy\n\n## Origin and Development of Blood Cells\n\nThe first **blood cells** appear around the **18th day** of embryonic development. Their origin occurs in three important stages.\n\nInitially, they come from the **umbilical vesicle**, where **primitive megaloblasts** are found. This phase lasts for the first two months.\n\nFrom the beginning of the **second month**, a second wave of blood production emerges from the **liver**.\n\nIt is only around the **third month** that some of this production begins to occur in the **bone marrow**.\n\nWe can observe here a development from the periphery to the centre: first the **umbilico-pedicular** period, then the **hepatic** period, and finally the bone marrow for **red blood cells**.\n\n## The Vestige of Vitelline Development: The Mesenteric Artery\n\nThe only vestige that will remain of this vitelline development is the **mesenteric artery**.\n\nIt served as an axis of rotation, a **fulcrum**, for the rotation and development of the **intestinal loop**.\n\nWhen the **amniotic cavity** forms all around, the vitelline vesicle, which contains the original cells for circulation, reintegrates.\n\nIn part, with the vitelline vesicle, the **embryonic pedicle** will form the **umbilical colon** with the placenta. The vestige that will connect is the **mesenteric system** (the superior vesicle). This axis of rotation is crucial for embryonic development.\n\n## The Movement of the Heart and the Aortic Arch\n\nWhen we observe the heart, we see the **aortic arch**. Symbolically, we can say that it goes up or down.\n\nThis movement of the aortic arch represents the **heartbeat**. It almost reproduces a developmental movement.\n\nThe aortic arch performs a **twisting** or **untwisting** movement during the cardiac cycle.\n\nWhen the heart pushes, the aortic arch opens to absorb blood. When the heart empties, it closes, performing a particular movement.\n\nIt opens to take blood and closes to eject it, which intrinsically links the aortic arch to the function of the heart.\n\n## The Aortic Arch and the Cardiac Cycle\n\nIt's a bit like a **basketball** player. When the heart rises, that's when the aorta ejects its blood volume.\n\nIt is important to know that the aorta contains almost as much blood in its volume as the heart on the arterial level.\n\nThis means that the aorta actively participates in the **systolic ejection** of blood.\n\nThis is supported by the **fascial environment**, which could be compared to a **\"fishnet stocking\"**.\n\n## The Rhythmic Zone: A Vital Fascial Crossroads\n\nThe aortic arch, the **bronchial bifurcation**, and the **oesophagus** are connected by a common **fascia**, which holds them together.\n\nThis area, characterised by the bronchial bifurcation, is what is called the **rhythmic zone point**.\n\nConsider the vital rhythms: **100,000 heartbeats** in 24 hours, **23,000 breaths** in 24 hours, and **1,000 to 2,000 swallows**.\n\nIt is a large rhythmic zone that joins and attaches between **T3**, **T4**, and **T5**. These vertebrae form a fascial equilibrium plane for the rhythmic zone, which is both **cardiac**, **pleural**, and **digestive**.\n\nWe have the aorta, the heart, and below, a very important bifurcation: the **iliac arteries**. Above, there is yet another level.\n\nIn fact, all of this forms a unitary and pure plane. We observe that certain pathologies of the **coxo-femoral** type or others can destabilise the heart. Conversely, what happens in these rotation phases can manifest up to the level of the heart."
