        "title": "13- The Heart_Diastole & Systole",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# 13 - The Heart: Diastole & Systole\n\nThe **heart** stores **energy** in a **fascial** environment, thereby supporting its **electrical activity**, in both its ascending and descending phases.\n\nThere is an **innate predisposition** in some individuals, who may manifest either **systolic** or **diastolic** function. A balance between these two functions is normally required. The heart repeats its embryonic movement quite directly.\n\n## Heart Movements and Emotional Implications\n\nA specific movement can be felt. For example, people who are overly oriented towards a **systolic** movement are often searching, but can also quickly become exhausted. Conversely, others start from this point and constantly seek a lower point of support.\n\n## Ventricular Looping and Cardiac Phases\n\nThe heart performs a characteristic **looping**, where the **ventricular** system, initially superior, becomes inferior, with a crucial point of support between the **atria** and the **ventricles**.\n\n* **During systole:**\n  * The heart performs an **upward movement**.\n  * It performs a **supination** movement.\n  * It tends to **verticalise**.\n  * It performs an **untwisting** movement.\n\nIt is at this moment that the **aorta** opens to receive all the blood, causing **congestion**.\n\n* **During diastole (descent):**\n  * All the blood from the aorta is ejected into the system.\n\nIt is sometimes easy to confuse the systolic movement with the descending movement. Systole is the moment of **ejection**. When the heart descends again, it **refills**.\n\nWhen the volume is ejected, the pressure in the aortic arch system increases. At the moment of descent, the heart fills while ejecting the aorta.\n\n## Heart Orientation: Verticalisation vs. Horizontalisation\n\nDo you have the impression that the heart tends to **verticalise** or **horizontalise**? Does it verticalise and ascend, or horizontalise and descend?\n\n## Points of Support for Observation\n\nWe will take three points of support:\n\n1. At the level of the **aortic space** (second intercostal space).\n2. At the level of the **pulmonary space**.\n3. The **hypothenar eminence** will rest on the apex of the heart.\n\n## The Heart's Influential Systems\n\nThe heart reacts according to two major systems that are very close to it and tends to assist them as much as possible:\n\n* The **liver**\n* The **stomach**\n* The **lungs**\n* The **kidneys**\n\nIt always seeks to maintain this pressure in its environment. The heart is a **volume regulator**. The heart should be considered as a large artery extending with the aorta, like an **octopus**.\n\n## Supination and Pronation Movements\n\nWe will have a **supination** movement, then a **pronation** movement.\n\n## Manual Assessment and Fascial Reactivity\n\nWe will observe the environment and how it is arranged. Then, we will place our hands at the level of the liver and observe its reaction on a **fascial** plane.\n\nThe aorta, if you observe it well anatomically, actually starts quite posteriorly, which makes it difficult to visualise. However, it shares a common fascial environment with the **bronchi** and the **oesophagus**, which insert at the level of a vertebra often in adaptation.\n\n## Rhythmic Zones and Diaphragmatic Relationship\n\nThere are:\n\n* A **neurosensory** zone.\n* A **rhythmic** zone.\n* A **metabolic** zone.\n* A **urogenital** zone.\n\nFor good movement, the heart must have a good relationship with the **diaphragm**. There is a direct relationship via the fascial continuity of the arch and the aorta.\n\nRemember the very deep passage of the aorta, where the **diaphragmatic crura** insert on either side. To work on the heart, it is essential that the diaphragm is **open** and **flexible**. Do not forget the other important passage at the level of the oesophagus.\n\n## Practical Application: Following Fascial Movements\n\nWe have studied the **embryonic pre-pattern fulcrum** which is positioned at the primitive streak level, at the coccyx, with the arrival point.\n\nNow, place your hand at the level of the heart and let it follow the fascial movement. The tissue, if you are attentive, will indicate whether the heart leans more towards systole or diastole.\n\nIs it my liver reacting? Is it in relation to my stomach? Or is it in relation to my kidneys? (Three levels). Then, we will observe if this can rebalance in relation to this observation."
