        "title": "16- Structuring of the Venous System 1_ The Cardinal Veins",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Structuring the Venous System: The Cardinal Veins\n\n## The Three General Venous Systems\n\nThree main **venous systems** are identified within the body:\n\n*   **The neurocranial system:** Corresponds to the vertebral plexus.\n*   **The viscerocranial system:** Linked to the portal system.\n*   **The internal system (internal man):** Represented by the inferior and superior vena cava system.\n\n## Embryological Origins of the Venous Systems\n\nFrom an **embryological** perspective, the formation of these systems is linked to three precursors:\n\n*   **The common cardinal:** Gives rise to the neurocranium, the vertebral plexus, and the caval system (inferior and superior).\n*   **The vitelline:** Essentially linked to the viscerocranium.\n*   **The umbilical:** Largely disappears, leaving a terminal fibrous system. A persistent terminal vessel can form **Meckel's diverticulum**, a small pouch located just before the ileocaecal valve, which can be the origin of diverticulitis.\n\n## The Cardinal System\n\nThe cardinal system is divided into:\n\n*   **Superior or anterior cardinal vein:** Located laterally superiorly.\n*   **Posterior or inferior cardinal vein (or mesonephrotic):** Located laterally inferiorly.\n\nThese cardinal veins are also called **mesometric veins**. Together, they correspond to what is called the **venous sinus**. The umbilical vein and the vitelline vein are located in the middle.\n\n## Fate of the Cardinal, Umbilical, and Vitelline Veins\n\n*   **Umbilical veins:** Disappear, leaving only vestiges.\n*   **Right cardinal vein:** The part between the sinus and the thymic vein disappears. However, the right thymic vein anastomoses with the left thymic vein to form the **brachiocephalic vein**.\n*   **Vitelline vein:** The left part disappears. The right part remains and anastomoses with the right anterior cardinal vein to form the **inferior vena cava**.\n\n## The Components of the Vessel and Changes in Trajectory\n\nFor a vessel to exist, four components are necessary:\n\n1.  The **trajectory**.\n2.  The **metabolic concentration**.\n3.  **Vacuolisation**.\n4.  The **interstitial fluid**.\n\nThe disappearance of part of a vein indicates the loss of one of these components. A new trajectory then forms. Vascular development occurs laterally towards the centre and segmentally.\n\nThe vascular system of the internal man is characterised by the common cardinal vein and the posterior cardinal vein, resulting from assimilation and disassimilation phenomena.\n\n## Development of the Heart and Great Vessels\n\nThe heart develops from the **primitive streak**, relying on a movement of concentration towards the midline. This process includes the **corrosion field**, the **heart looping**, and its placement to the left. A longitudinal concentration axis is followed by the looping, creating a perpetual movement of the heart. Then follows the more horizontal placement of the great vessels, particularly pulmonary and aortic.\n\nThe cardinal system develops more posteriorly, while the umbilical and vitelline systems are more anterior.\n\n## The Subcardinal and Supracardinal Veins\n\nFrom the cardinal network, the **subcardinal veins** emerge at the base of the posterior cardinal veins.\n\n*   Most of the left subcardinal vein regresses.\n*   The right subcardinal vein loses its connection with the posterior cardinal vein and develops a new anastomosis with the vitelline vein, participating in the formation of the caval system. This part will form the **inferior vena cava**, located between the liver and the kidney.\n\nDerivatives of these subcardinals include the **suprarenal** vein, the **testicular** veins, the left renal part of the inferior vena cava, and the supracardinal.\n\nThis process is a \"budding\" by an aspiration field, creating new segmental trajectories while others disappear. The subcardinals re-bud to form a second network, and the process repeats with the supracardinals.\n\n## The Subsequent Fate of the Venous Networks\n\nThe only final vestige of the cardinal system will eventually be the **azygos system**. It will be replaced by the subcardinal, then supracardinal systems.\n\n*   Inferiorly, the iliac system is initially cardinal, but this system disappears.\n*   The subcardinal, partly disappeared, contributes to the purple segment that forms the inferior vena cava. This vein is a combination of part of the subcardinal and part of the supracardinal.\n\nThis development occurs in a transverse movement. As a result, some segments of the inferior vena cava come from the supracardinal, with some vestiges of the subcardinal.\n\nThe developmental movement of the subcardinal is characterised by \"spotting\", a segmental budding that contains the entire network of the system.\n\n## Drainage of Different Areas\n\n*   **Azygos-hemiazygos system:** Ensures all thoracic drainage.\n*   **Mesodermal system (internal man):** Includes renal, spermatic, and suprarenal drainage.\n\nThe movement from the periphery to the centre is clearly visible. The supracardinal gives the entire thoracic and abdominal part, with a segmental difference for the left side (hemiazygos) and the right side (azygos).\n\nThe fusion of these networks in the abdominal region forms the **inferior vena cava**, which drains the entire system of the mesodermal man (support tissue).\n\n## Key Residual Venous Structures\n\nThe only final vestiges are:\n\n*   **The brachiocephalic trunk.**\n*   **The superior vena cava.**\n*   **The iliac veins** below.\n*   **In the centre:** The meeting on the caval plane with renal, suprarenal (mesodermal type) and azygos structures.\n*   **On the left and right:** Hemiazygos and azygos, ensuring thoraco-abdominal drainage on the mesodermal plane."
