        "title": "17- Structuring of the Venous System 2_The Vitelline & Umbilical System",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# 17 - Structuring the Venous System 2: The Vitelline & Umbilical System\n\n## The Vitelline System and the Liver\n\nThe **vitelline system** is the second major network we will discuss, linked to the digestive system. The **liver** is the main receptacle of this system.\n\nIt is essential to remember that the liver results from the combination of two tissues: a **mesodermal tissue** and an **endodermal tissue**.\n\nMy endodermal tube has a foregut, midgut, and hindgut. The liver emerges at the junction between the foregut and the midgut, initially developing as a \"field of aspiration,\" a subtle description of the digestive tissue.\n\nThe **20 vitelline veins**, mesodermal structures, are at the origin of liver formation.\n\n### Sequence of Liver Development\n\n**Cephalisation** leads to **cardialisation**, which causes **diaphragmatisation**. This process results in hepatic congestion at the mesodermal level, through vitelline integration.\n\nThe movement of cephalisation leads to that of cardialisation, then diaphragmatisation, leading to a phase of congestion under the diaphragm. This area of congestion corresponds to the mesodermal development of the liver. Initially, the liver receives no umbilical information but is informed by dissimilation products from the brain, lower trunk, and vitelline vesicle.\n\nIts first impulse is therefore a reception of **toxicity**. The liver, as an organ, has the primary function of receiving and transforming this toxicity, before having a regenerative impulse later.\n\n### Formation of the Hepatic Vascular Network\n\nWe have the **right vitelline vein** and the **left vitelline vein**, with a small anastomosis already formed between the two. In parallel, the hepatic cord originating from the endoderm develops.\n\nBetween these two vitelline veins, an entire network forms, congests, and organises. This network will eventually form the venous duct and, later, structures such as the **gastric vein** and the **gastro-epiploic vein**. An important area will develop: the **portal vein**.\n\nAt another level, the **umbilical vein** develops, part of which will be integrated while another part will disappear. This network of vitelline systems meets to form a specific vascular network, acting as a drainage system.\n\n### Segmentation of the Vitelline Vein\n\nDevelopment occurs under the **septum transversum**. The vitelline vein, located under this septum, can be divided into three sections:\n\n*   **Suprahepatic section:** This will eventually form the hepatic duct, then the hepatic vein. The right vitelline vein becomes the hepatic vein, the region of flow towards the heart.\n*   **Hepatic section.**\n*   **Infrahepatic section.**\n\nAnother derivative of this vitelline part is the superior part of the **inferior vena cava**.\n\n### Regressions and Modifications of Drainage\n\nRegressions occur. The left umbilical vein regresses, but part of the right umbilical vein persists, forming a link for the **hepatic sinusoids**.\n\nThe umbilical vitelline vein is here. The left umbilical vein forms a link, then gradually disappears in its superior part. The **ductus venosus** will be formed with the portal trunk.\n\nIn the infrahepatic region, the left vitelline vein regresses but develops an anastomosis with the right vitelline vein, leading to a change in blood drainage. Blood passes from the left side of the abdominal viscera to the right vitelline vein, creating a developing transverse network. This leads to a **switch** from the left side to the right side on the venous plane, favouring growth on the right.\n\n### The Two Currents of the Hepatic Portal System\n\nAll blood coming from the **right mesenteric** side is drained by the portal system and is found mainly in the right liver. In contrast, everything inferior (stomach, spleen, and lower colon) drains more towards the left liver.\n\nTwo currents can be observed within the portal system itself:\n\n*   A current oriented towards the left side.\n*   Another towards the right side.\n\nThe liver plays a digestive and metabolic role, but also a motor and emotional one. Organs such as the stomach and spleen are related to the emotional system, dreams, and nightmares, leading to congestion.\n\nThe portal trunk is common here, but it is interesting to note that there is a flow that does not mix or can mix.\n\n### Liver Regeneration\n\nThe liver never regenerates at its endodermal level but always regenerates at its mesodermal level. It can rebuild vessels but not ducts.\n\nThe liver is a set of **bile ducts** integrated with many vessels. It is important to remember that the liver only regenerates at night. There are three levels:\n\n1.  **When you eat:** Lots of venous blood and little arterial blood. The liver does not regenerate.\n2.  **Between meals:** Balance between arterial and venous blood. The liver regenerates a little.\n3.  **At night, when you sleep:** Lots of arterial blood and little venous blood.\n\nFasting is beneficial because it allows the liver to regenerate and cells to become stronger, releasing energy from the inside out.\n\n### The Heart-Liver-Spleen-Small Intestine Functional Unit\n\nA rebalancing occurs between the heart, liver, spleen, and mesenteric system (small intestine). This constitutes a functional unit.\n\nThe liver is a volume regulator, capable of increasing or decreasing **blood volume**. It plays a crucial role in embryonic development and at birth.\n\nBone and tissue compressions, as well as vascular changes, are observed. It is crucial to treat these aspects on a fluid level at birth, in addition to the compressive level.\n\n### Importance of Confluences\n\nThe retrohepatic confluence is important for heart return. The **subhepatic confluence** and the **jugular confluence** represent two major keys.\n\nIt is essential not to overload the heart in terms of venous return. The heart must function correctly in systole, not in diastole. If the liver is systolic, it helps to resorb.\n\nIt is therefore necessary to release facial function to restore hepatic release. Do not forget the heart-liver-spleen connection.\n\n### Vitelline Vesicle and Umbilical Cord Connection\n\nThe movement of the amniotic cavity shows the vitelline vesicle regressing and depositing on the umbilical cord. A loop will develop, integrating the intestinal loop inside.\n\nIn the umbilical cord, the spiralling vessels in the embryonic pedicle connect, with the remnant of the **yolk sac**. The intestinal tube and the embryonic pedicle join, integrating the allantois and the entire process with the large amniotic cavity."
