        "title": "21- Summary of Vascular Structuring by the Amniotic Cavity",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Summary of Vascular Structuring by the Amniotic Cavity\n\n## The Origin and Integration of the Vascular System\n\nThe **vascular system**, at its periphery, is strongly integrated into the **vitelline system**. The **amniotic cavity**, initially the same size as the vitelline vesicle, plays a fundamental role.\n\nThe embryo elongates and grows considerably. The importance of this amniotic cavity lies in its ability to completely integrate the vitelline system. This movement is crucial and forms the central point of our study.\n\n## The Resorption Movement and Zone B\n\nIn this movement, the entire vitelline system resorbs towards the centre of the embryo, reintegrating the whole. This amniotic cavity, which can be referred to as **Zone B**, in relation to the aortic system, draws everything towards the centre.\n\nThis process occurs on both a **transverse abdominal** and **thoracic** plane.\n\nWith the growth and establishment of the heart, as well as the significant development of the brain, the amniotic cavity takes over. It completely encompasses the entire space of the **external coelom**. Only a part of this internal coelom will be integrated into an internal coelom. The more the amniotic cavity grows, the more the system integrates.\n\n## Arterial Integration and Embryonic Folding\n\nTwo key elements summarise the integration of the arterial system, from the periphery to the centre: **cephalisation** and **embryonic folding**. This includes cardialisation, diaphragmatisation, and hepatisation.\n\nThe amniotic cavity acts as an integrating movement, redefining spaces. In this dynamic, both horizontally and vertically, Zone B is constructed. The vitelline vesicle, containing primitive information at the venous level, interacts with the outside to reintegrate the body and the venous system.\n\n## The Role of Fluids and the Vitelline Vesicle\n\nThe secret lies in the **repatriation of fluids** towards the centre, with the fascial system playing a predominant role in this release.\n\nThe vitelline vesicle is a great source of information. The integration movement includes:\n\n- The transformation of the external coelom into an internal coelom.\n- The closure of the neural tube.\n- Integration and movement towards the centre.\n- Construction, orchestrated by the cavity.\n\n## Restoring the Cavity and Zone B\n\nThe objective is to restore this cavity and Zone B to reintegrate internal circulation.\n\nVisualising the diagram as a person lying down:\n\n- In blue, integration into a neural tube.\n- The rest forming the skin, an **ectodermal** layer.\n\nSimultaneously, the integration of the vitelline vesicle contributes to forming part of the digestive system, while the entire venous system integrates. The movement to follow is that of the growing amniotic cavity, leading to a fusion to form the longitudinal part, the digestive tube.\n\nThe integration of the external coelom into a future internal coelom is visualised in yellow, where everything converges on the midline.\n\n## The Great Engine: Notochordal System and Neural Tube\n\nThe main engine of this process is the **notochordal system**, which influences the neural tube and organises the primitive aortic vascular system. It redirects information with the progressive integration of the entire transverse system, from the periphery to the centre.\n\nWe will follow this movement step by step. It is essential to \"allow\" primary respiration.\n\n## Endovoluntary Movement of the Lungs and Awareness of the Umbilical Pedicle\n\nThe **endovoluntary movement of the lungs** originates from the endoderm and is guided by the vascular system. Awareness of the **umbilical pedicle** must return to this space, allowing one to perceive the force of the growing amniotic cavity, while integrating the processes of cephalisation, cardialisation, diaphragmatisation, and hepatisation.\n\nThe return then occurs. The vitelline vesicle, driven by differential growth speed, will be reincorporated into the diagram. It will push the pedicle to rejoin the vitelline vesicle and later form the umbilical cord.\n\nEverything converges here, starting from a pedicle to return to a cord."
