        "title": "22- Practice of Vascular System Structuring",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Vascular System Structuring Practice\n\nWe will look for the **stillness** of zone C relative to zone A on the diaphragmatic plane. There is a point of stillness in the room.\n\nI will guide you at some point. We will start from **neutral** and gradually allow the patient's neutral to develop. We will focus on the **micro-crystalline field**, taking up all the space.\n\nTo achieve the most effective therapeutic action possible, it is essential to reach a neutral state. Then, it is important to bring out this neutral state in the patient. This is a process that needs to **mature**.\n\nFor this, we need the **meeting point**. Once I have established this meeting point, the person, with confidence, can gradually disengage, let go, and move towards their neutral state.\n\nGradually, these two neutral states will begin to blend. Once these two neutral states blend, a more visible space, an **emergence**, can appear: what is called **primary respiration**.\n\nPrimary respiration is not only present in the body; it is omnipresent, much like the **breath of life**.\n\nWe will focus on the **amniotic cavity**, this zone B. At the same time, we will dissociate our attention to focus on the **diaphragmatic crura**.\n\nThe most fixed point of my diaphragm is formed by the crura. We will observe that, ultimately, we will reach a neutral state. These are enormous points of support, almost a silent point.\n\nWith a little patience, we will bring out the neutral state more broadly, also using **crystalline stillness**.\n\nWe will rather speak of the **crystalline immobility** of the room. There is a form of immobility in zone C that we must perceive. We will let the body centre itself in relation to this zone C.\n\nAlthough this may seem subtle, it will happen naturally on a **fluidic**, almost electrical, plane.\n\nThen, we will begin to merge this stillness of the room, or this dynamic immobility of the room, with the dynamic immobility at the level of the diaphragmatic crura.\n\nWhile being aware of the amniotic cavity and the integration of my **vitelline vesicle** to form my venous system, we will merge this stillness of the room with the dynamic immobility.\n\nIt is crucial to surrender completely to **primary respiration**, to the present movement, to the tide, that is, to the **therapeutic force**, to the power.\n\nGradually, let's see what this can generate. The goal, in **non-action**, is not to induce, but to trust the osteopath."
