        "title": "25- Practical Notes Before Approaching the Liver",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Practice Before Approaching the Liver\n\nIn this session, we will explore the **liver** in relation to its **overall environment**. It is essential not to adopt an overly **selective** or **local** approach.\n\nThe liver plays a central role in the organisation of the lesser sac of the **omentum**, the positioning of the **stomach**, the axis of the **spleen**, and the **greater omentum**. We will practice on the liver while considering its relationship with the **heart** and the lesser sac of the omentum, using an appropriate handhold.\n\nThe objective is to allow the liver to regain its **motility**, as it is this motility that creates its function. We will begin with a **neutral** and superficial contact, which will gradually deepen as the **primary respiration** manifests. The meeting of these two neutrals is what brings forth the **therapeutic process**.\n\nThe liver is crucial in the organisation of the embryo, particularly in the **transverse** axis and the establishment of the **gastro-duodeno-pancreatico-lineal** axis, thus managing all movement. This tilting, which we previously discussed with the **venous** and **arterial** network, is an essential developmental movement for growth. The liver moves upon itself, not by rotation, but by **displacement**, which gives it developmental strength.\n\nThis embryological motility is fundamental. When we place our hands, we must position ourselves in a **fulcrum** where the entire system can develop. If we limit ourselves to a local approach, we lose sight of the original fulcrum.\n\nThe closer we get to the embryonic fulcrum, the more we access this force, and the more the body can provide us with information, because it knows it. A high frequency promotes **regenerative power**. Consider the word \"fulcrum\" as a **function** rather than a simple point of support.\n\nThe **midline**, for example, is a fulcrum for the totality. We have identified the heart area as an embryonic fulcrum, which cannot be reduced to a simple point.\n\nWorking on motility related to **brain** development can serve as a tool. Let's recall the curvatures, this \"tai chi\" of the brain:\n\n- **Expansion**\n- **Cephalic flexion**\n- **Cervical flexion**\n- **Pontine flexion**\n- **Telencephalisation**\n\nThe telencephalisation phase is crucial, as it induces the straightening and establishment of the **anterior white line**. This involves the formation of the **star**.\n\nWe can work solely on motility or use **specific points** such as:\n\n- The tip of the **monotocortex**\n- The **supraocciput**\n- The base of the **occiput**\n- The **presphenoid**\n\nThese points are related to these developments. For example, the tip of the monotocortex is an important reference point in **submesencephalic flexion**.\n\nI can thus search for the **point of stillness** in the developing system, depending on the support points on which I position myself. Certain phases will unfold simultaneously, illustrating the **synchronicity** of development.\n\nRegarding brain development, an important vestige is found at the level of the **mesenteric system**. The **vitelline** or **mesenteric** axis is crucial for re-energising a developing brain.\n\nVascularly, it is important to note that the brain is entirely dependent on the heart for its function and formation. The heart continuously informs the brain, and a **pulsation** is present within it.\n\nKeep in mind the image of the **septum transversum** coiling with the establishment of the liver, integrated with the **vitelline vesicle**. The establishment of the **amniotic cavity** is the result of our previous work.\n\nThere is a developmental motility movement generated by the liver, which organises the entire **hepato-gastro-duodeno-pancreatico-lineal** system. We observe the tilting of the heart on its left axis, an inverse movement at the overall hepatic level, and a counter-rotation at the digestive level.\n\nWe will first work on this large **subdiaphragmatic** organisational centre, by establishing the lesser sac of the omentum. Then, we will examine the relationship between the liver and the heart, which will be our two working points.\n\nWe have the **cardiac imprint**, the **pulmonary imprint**, and the enormous **hepatic imprint**. We will perform work on the liver in relation to the establishment of the heart and the intestine, adopting a **biodynamic** approach.\n\nThis means that we will place our hands and allow the movement to occur. We may have a movement that seeks or a movement that expresses its originality. We will provide this point so that the system can reorganise itself.\n\nThe liver is a **specialisation** to be considered as a **fractal expansion** of the intestine. It consists of a set of **bile ducts** with two types of information:\n\n- **Vascular** type information, corresponding to the **portal** type liver.\n- A completely red face may indicate a **mesodermal** type liver problem.\n- A completely yellow face may indicate an **endodermal** type liver problem.\n\nThese two approaches allow for a complementary understanding of the system."
