        "duration": "03:58",
        "title": "26- Liver Practice",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Liver Practice: Movement and Therapeutic Approach\n\n## The Liver's Growth Movement and its Anatomical Relationships\n\nThe **liver**, through its **growth movement**, significantly influences the arrangement of neighbouring organs. It initiates a **sub-diaphragmatic tilt**.\n\nThis growth impacts the positioning of the **stomach**, as well as the **retro-gastric pouch**. The **duodenum** and the **spleen** are also dependent on this considerable expansion of the liver.\n\nFrom a **facial** perspective, this entire system is suspended from the **aorta**. This is a crucial reference axis, as it constitutes the main pathway of the **trophic gate**, around which the system appears to pivot.\n\n## Supporting the Liver's Developmental Movement\n\nTo support this movement, I position myself slightly above the **costal arch**. My goal is to exaggerate the movement to visualise it, but it is a **pure developmental** movement.\n\nI place myself in **embryonic listening**, first establishing my **neutral**. My hands are placed, gently encompassing, without exerting excessive pressure.\n\nThe image to remember is that of **ants**: one must neither crush them nor let them escape. In my mind, I visualise the aortic vascular axis.\n\nAt the end of exhalation, I connect to this specific quality of the liver, which seeks to return to its source, to move slightly backwards. I let it do so.\n\n## First Sensation and Fulcrum\n\nMy first sensation is that it is not completely free in its movement. It seeks to **regenerate**.\n\nI place a **fulcrum** with my elbow, without too much force, and I provide this fulcrum with my **primary respiration**. I let the neutral settle and the system manifest itself.\n\nWe will take the axis of the **heart** and the **vena cava**. The movement is a little more delicate, difficult to mimic.\n\n## Awareness of Space and the Therapeutic Neutral\n\nThe second step is **awareness of space**, the opening and perception of this space. Then comes the essential notion of the **neutral**.\n\nWhen this neutral begins to mature, little by little, the two neutrals meet. It is at this moment that the process becomes **therapeutic**.\n\n**Impatience** is an obstacle; if we create a space of impatience, this meeting cannot take place. The process is there, and it is at this stage that one can dare to let primary respiration act.\n\nI know there is a great desire to intervene, but this practice can also be done on other levels. I am teaching an **energetic**, embryonic approach here, but one can very well work on facial planes, etc. My observation is that other approaches do not hold as well."
