        "title": "34-The Lower Genital Tract",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# The Lower Genital Tract: A Biodynamic Approach\n\n## Embryology of the Vagina and Uterus\n\nThe insertion of the **bladder** at the level of the **Müllerian tubercle**, located in the urogenital sinus, is essential. This area includes the bladder, urethra, and the attachment to the vagina.\n\nThe vagina derives from the **mesoderm**, specifically the Müllerian duct. The formation of the **vaginal plates** results from the posterior growth of the sacrum and the neural tube.\n\nThe differential growth rate of this posterior part creates the opening space of the vagina. It is the **postero-anterior** movement, between the kidney and the sacrum, that allows this extension.\n\nThe Müllerian tubercle thickens and is then stretched, not by superficial traction, but by the faster push of the posterior part. This phenomenon leads to the lengthening and formation of the vagina and cervix.\n\nThe posterior wall of the urogenital sinus thickens, giving rise to the vaginal plates which open and stretch. This dynamic is similar, with the posterior part growing faster.\n\n## Gynaecological Balance and Biodynamic Movement\n\nDuring the examination of the uterus, a movement between the **sacrum** and the **peritoneum** is perceived. It is in the interaction of these two poles that vaginal and uterine balance is found.\n\nAt the gonadal level, an inverse movement is felt in the abdomen, following the ligament towards the pubis, like a descending wave.\n\nThe descent of the sacrum is influenced by the neural tube. Another crucial fulcrum is the combination of the pubis and the sacrum, forming an essential fascial balance of the female lesser pelvis.\n\nThis balance involves a descending line of force relative to the sacrum, influencing various functions of the female body.\n\n## Therapeutic Approach to Uterine Imbalances\n\nSituations such as **miscarriages** leave an energetic imprint in the uterus. An energetic cleansing of the uterus then becomes necessary.\n\nWe can approach the uterus with a **magnetic force**, learning to feel the energetic field at a distance. The practitioner perceives a frequency, an area of heat that densifies, a sign of the energy present.\n\nMy approach consists of \"scanning\" and identifying the areas requiring cleansing. This involves restoring freedom to tissues and energies.\n\nA **retroverted uterus**, for example, can lead to congestive phases. The remote work aims to rebalance the gynaecological system, in close connection with **gastrin**.\n\n**Endometriosis**, characterised by a proliferation of tissue migrating into the peritoneum, is often associated with lower back and sacroiliac pain.\n\n## The Intraperitoneal Cavity and the Transgenerational Dimension\n\nIn women, there is a direct link between the cervix, fallopian tubes, and the **intraperitoneal cavity**. This cavity is of great importance, perceived as a \"sky\" or a primordial space.\n\nEach state of the body represents the best possible functional response at a given moment. This response is influenced by our life, but also by that of our ancestors.\n\nA retroverted uterus, for example, can be the best response the body has found to resolve a **transgenerational** or deep personal problem.\n\nIt is essential to understand why a transgenerational pattern manifests in this way. Therapy aims to decode this \"best response\" and offer the necessary release, if requested.\n\nThe embryo perfectly illustrates this notion: at each stage of development, it presents the best possible physiological response.\n\n## Secondary Neurulation and Filum Terminale Formation\n\nThe **neural tube** is associated with a posterior caudal eminence, creating a space of light and connection. We observe the caudal bud and the terminal part of the **notochord**.\n\nThe space of the rectum and the neural tube with the posterior neuropore are in close relation. A connection is formed through a more pronounced developmental movement at the posterior part.\n\nThis involves a closure then a reopening to establish this connection. This process leads to the emergence of the posterior neuropore and the lengthening to form the **filum terminale**.\n\nThis is what is called **secondary neurulation**. Manipulation of the sacrum reveals these differential growth rates, where the initial junction lengthens posteriorly.\n\nThe integration of the caudal eminence ensures continuity with the neural tube, forming this ascending secondary neurulation.\n\n## Perineal Development and Hepatic Influence\n\nAt the level of the **perineum**, we observe the emergence of the lower limbs and a traction that is exerted. This movement is deeply linked to the uterine system.\n\nThe tilting of the **liver**, in synergy with the descent of the neural tube and the sacrum, influences the developmental movement that pulls towards the linea alba, via the falciform ligament.\n\nThis hepatic development leads to a tilt that affects the entire developing uterine area. It could explain phenomena of migration or differential traction related to uterine position.\n\nA ligament develops between the pubis and the umbilicus, encapsulating the history of uterine descent and formation.\n\nJust as the sternum contains the history of our flexion, this ventromedial ligament (on the linea alba) concentrates the history of all posterior formation, of the **gonadisation** and **uterisation** of the pelvis.\n\nThe linea alba is the meeting point of all **urogenital** history."
