        "title": "36-Practice_The Genital System",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# The Genital System: Biodynamic Practice\n\nI will show you two ways to prepare the **female pelvis** to rebalance it and work on the **birth axis**. This approach is also valid for the **uterine** or **prostatic system**. However, there is a fundamental difference: men do not have to give birth or carry a child.\n\n## Balancing the Female Pelvis\n\n### Identifying the axis and imbalance\n\nWe will identify the **tubercle of the third adductor**, present on both sides. By referring to these two tubercles, I can determine the **pelvic axis** in space. If the pelvis is unbalanced, for example, if one side is slightly sunken and too short, this indicates an imbalance.\n\n### Biodynamic rebalancing technique\n\nTo balance this structure, I position myself in **biodynamics**. I hold the woman's pelvis, supporting it at different points. The goal is to support the entire pelvis while having the axis in front of me. I then allow biodynamics to operate. I refer to my central line and take a precise fulcrum.\n\nI work with a **support triangle**, but without exerting excessive pressure. This awareness of support allows the pelvis to reposition itself in relation to the fulcrum.\n\n### Alternative in case of difficulty\n\nIf this method is not sufficient, I can use another fulcrum. By palpating, I can already determine the birth axis, which is crucial. If the pelvis remains unbalanced, I position myself behind the patient and lean on the **ischium**. I then let the process unfold naturally, with the patient standing relatively upright. With a good fulcrum from my hands, I let the body work to rebalance problems in the lesser pelvis.\n\n## Benefits and specific considerations\n\n### Decongestion and circulation\n\nThis technique promotes **decongestion**. A good recentring of the pelvis helps to release the **vascular system**, thus facilitating the evacuation of congestion.\n\n### Pregnancy and positioning\n\nWhen a woman is pregnant, it is not always easy to position her on her back, especially if she suffers from severe lower back pain. In this case, it is preferable to avoid lying her down so as not to undo the work done during the straightening. I prefer to let the space and **primary respiration** work.\n\n### Control and verification\n\nDuring pregnancy, I systematically check the birth axis and the freedom of the feet. I position myself behind if necessary and let the body rebalance itself; the surrounding space will guide this process.\n\n### Role of fascia in childbirth\n\nIt is fundamental to know that during birth, the child is guided by the **fascia of the pelvis**. If the pelvis is unbalanced, the child could become stuck during the birth movement."
