        "title": "6-Practical Notions",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Practical Concepts in Osteopathy\n\nWhen there is a **profound transformation** of the system, a sudden change can occur. This evokes a **transformative training**, where one modifies their form. This process can be compared to an **alchemical level** that generates **tissue** and **energetic** change. At this stage, it is possible to reconnect with the **wave of impermanence** of life.\n\nEnergy 1 transforms into energy 2, leading to a **transformation**. This moment can be chaotic, and the person may feel **isolated**. It is essential to be present, not only through words but also through gestures and a gaze that must be **liberating**. The goal is to bring the person back to **trust** in life, sometimes even transcending the notion of life and death.\n\nThis **presence** implies being here and now, listening, and returning to a state of **freedom**. In this state, there are no longer any brakes, because one is in the **movement of life**, which manifests in the **gift of the present**. Often, due to a lack of understanding of our **emotional context**, we react rather than act. This means we give others the power to decide our existence.\n\nThe **second cervical vertebra**, known as the **axis**, has a small tooth, the **odontoid process**, which is symbolically connected to a **silver thread**. This vertebra is essential for connecting our egoistic intelligence to higher levels of consciousness. It is crucial to connect this vertebra to the **pineal gland** and the **pituitary gland**, thereby allowing us to reach higher aspects of the self, such as the **atma**, the **manas**, and the **buddhi**. This means integrating **love**, **wisdom**, and **divine will**.\n\nThis initiatory process allows us to connect to levels of consciousness of which we may not be aware. We are on an **axis** where the development of the **notochordal process** is influenced by the environment. Indeed, form is dependent on the outside, and trophically, we nourish ourselves from the universe, whether from land or sea.\n\nThe **sphenobasilar synchondrosis** is also a reflection of **occlusion**. The type of occlusion impacts the synchondrosis, because the body, at the level of the teeth, is the densest part and the one that absorbs stress. It is therefore crucial to maintain the best possible **mobility**. Modifications, such as changing an amalgam, profoundly affect the body structure.\n\nThe base of the skull and the principle of the **notochord** are integrated into **postural globality**. The teeth act as **postural sensors**, connected to every organ and tissue, and any modification can have repercussions on the entire posture. An important response occurs at the level of the **pituitary gland**, in relation to the **hypothalamus**, which receives information on the integrity of the **acid-base** system.\n\nThus, there is a **chemical tone** in relation to the environment, and we constantly seek to rebalance ourselves through movement. Each breath modifies our balance, and the renal system plays a crucial role in **oxidation-reduction** and base balance.\n\nThe expression of our posture and our face reflects our best adaptation to the present moment. On a symbolic level, the **sphenobasilar synchondrosis** represents the harmony between different bodily structures. The base of the skull receives visceral and neuronal information, and all the tension membranes of the **dural sheaths** influence this region.\n\nThe **Circle of Willis** is a key element that integrates neurological information and the tissue quality of the body. Furthermore, the **lymphatic** system is a place for receiving information, constantly seeking to maintain balance. By restoring **silence**, it is possible to initiate a reorganisation that promotes health."
