        "title": "9- influence of embryonic folding on the upper digestive tract",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Influence of Embryonic Folding on the Upper Gastrointestinal Tract\n\nThe **importance of embryonic folding** is evident in the upper part of the intestine. This **flexion** movement of the embryo leads to significant changes in its development.\n\nDuring folding, the **mesenchyme**, which is the mesenchymal tissue beneath the brain, becomes perpendicular to the embryo's longitudinal axis. This movement creates a distinct curvature, leading to **compression** between the front and back, which contributes to the formation of the skull base. This dynamic process generates a **cartilaginous field** that, initially loose, gradually densifies to form compressed **primitive cartilages**, thereby releasing significant energy.\n\nThe **amniotic cavity** and the **vitelline cavity** play a crucial role in this development. As the embryo folds, the vitelline cavity shifts, and the neural tube begins to curl. The cardiac region, initially anterior, is also influenced by this flexion movement.\n\nThe study of this movement proceeds from the periphery inwards, from the visible face, such as the mouth, to the pharyngeal gut. This flexion movement organises the **distinctive features of the face**. The **notochord** induces the neural tube and arteries, while the coiling around the arterial system becomes organised.\n\nThe upper part of the intestine forms as an **articulation** between the heart and the brain. The **foregut** appears, representing the developing upper intestine. This articulation is oriented and organised in space-time by the **amniotic fluid**, with the vascular system as its fulcrum.\n\nThe heart, visible in an elevated position, and the coiling of embryonic structures illustrate this articulation. The further development progresses, the stronger the organisation becomes. The large vitelline sac and its remnant form, while the upper part organises through flexion movements.\n\nThe **amniotic cavity** and the heart create a space that becomes an articulation between the heart and the brain, propelled by amniotic growth. This process marks the beginning of the formation of the digestive tract, which organises along a longitudinal plane. The delimitation of the upper part of the intestine begins, integrating the **allantois** and the **cloacal membrane**.\n\nBetween this membrane and the pharyngeal membrane, the mouths at the buccal level develop. This articulation between the brain, the amniotic sac, and the heart is organised by the differential growth rate of the vascular system, establishing a balance between the brain and the heart, oriented by the **mesoderm**.\n\nThe appearance of a vessel depends on various components: a field, metabolic concentration, a trajectory, **vacuolations**, and the presence of interstitial particles. These elements are dynamic, which explains why some vessels may appear and disappear during embryonic development. Initially, two large aortas centralise into a single aorta.\n\nThe influence of this folding is therefore essential for organising the **internal delimitation** of the digestive tract. We will now delve into the details of this process."
