        "title": "10-Formation of the Upper Intestine",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Formation of the Upper Intestine\n\nThe formation of the upper intestine is a complex process involving the movement of the **endoderm**. This movement manifests both as a whole and **transversely**, transforming a sac into a tube. The **amniotic cavity** plays a key role in this movement, completely encompassing the embryo and integrating the digestive tract from the outside inwards, primarily guided by the primitive **aortic frenum**.\n\nFocusing on the **vascular** plane, we observe that the primitive endocardial tubes approach each other simultaneously with the closure of the neural tube. This meeting creates a space in the lumen of the primitive **vitelline endoderm**, forming what is known as the **pharyngeal intestine**. This process occurs on the midline, while laterally, **cellulose** appears.\n\nThe differential growth of **epithelial tissue** relative to **connective tissue** allows the two aortas to approach each other on the central axis, thereby delimiting the longitudinal axis and creating the pharyngeal intestine. The upper intestine extends from the mouth to the median part, involving the formation of the face.\n\nAt approximately fifteen days, the end of the second week, the embryo can be divided into three parts: the **upper third**, the **middle third**, and the **lower third**. The head of the future embryo is disproportionate to a small trunk, with the cephalic part already identifiable. Half of the embryo is located at the base of the skull, in relation to the **notochordal field** relative to the primitive streak.\n\nThe flexion of the embryo is influenced by the vascular system. A simple diagram shows that a tube bends, with one area densifying and another stretching, thus forming **plicatures**. Internally, the tissue is **endodermal**, while externally it is **ectodermal**, with **mesodermal** tissue in between. The branchial arches, organised in space relative to the embryo, contain specific information.\n\nEach branchial arch is oriented towards the base of the skull. The mandibular arches, for example, converge towards this base. Treating a face or a skull involves restoring this primitive function, by re-establishing an **energy field** that organises towards this space.\n\nFour major functional branchial arches can be identified: the **mandibular arch**, the **hyoid arch**, the **superior laryngeal arch**, and the **inferior laryngeal arch**. Each arch, whether ectodermal, mesodermal, or endodermal, contains specific information. The mandibular arch, for example, is linked to the mandibular cartilage and structures of the **inner ear**. Therefore, a destabilisation of the jaw can affect the internal organisation of the ear.\n\nThe process of embryonic flexion and elongation is also linked to **cerebralisation** and the formation of the **prosencephalic system**. This development occurs in a **biodynamic** process, where the embryo begins to fold and open. The heart develops between the mental, the neural tube, and the liver, thus creating the face.\n\nThe rupture of the **buccopharyngeal membrane** marks the beginning of mouth formation, which develops horizontally due to compression between the heart and the brain. This compression integrates the mesodermal tissue, containing vascular information. The appearance of the **nasal pit** and the oral cavity is also linked to this dynamic.\n\nBrain development is related to the process of **telencephalisation**, which involves an ascent of the brain and a visceral descent. The face, initially, is a field of compression between the heart and the brain, and through the growth of the embryo, it opens.\n\nThe development of the **pterygoids** and the **palate** is influenced by brain traction and visceral descent. This synchronised movement between the digestive system and the heart, as well as cerebral ascent, contributes to the formation of the high-arched palate.\n\nOcclusal forces, pressures from the lingual mass, and piezoelectric effects also influence the formation of teeth and facial structures. Each tooth receives specific information, and treating the face or teeth requires rebalancing these structures with their embryonic origin.\n\nIn conclusion, the formation of the upper intestine and facial structures is a complex process, involving dynamic interactions between different embryonic tissues and their synchronised development."
