        "title": "22-Meditation_Mary's arm",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Meditation: The Brahmari Breath\n\nThere are **four essential stages** in the act of breathing. First, it is important to learn to be **aware of your breath**. Then, it is about following this breath with **mindfulness**. This mindfulness involves an **energy of concentration**, as it is necessary to pay attention for longer.\n\nScientific research shows that by working at this level, one develops more subtle **empathic faculties**, **compassion**, and **attention**, which contributes to our **happiness**. What I call **joy**.\n\nWhen one learns to stay with their breath and follow it, one begins to recognise their body, thus uniting **body and mind**. The fourth level consists of **relaxing the body**. Once these steps are completed, one enters the fifth level: **generating a feeling of joy**.\n\nIt is said that this teaching dates back to **Buddha**, who proposed **16 ways to generate breath**. We will practice an exercise focused on the **exhalation** act, known as **brahmari**, or bee breath. This technique has a very interesting effect on the **brain**, quickly bringing **calmness of mind** and **stress reduction**.\n\nThe tongue is considered the **bud of the heart**, and the **thyroid** originates from it. We speak with our heart, but also with the **frequency subtlety** of the thyroid. At a certain level, it is no longer the word that matters, but the **sound** and **frequency** that touch.\n\nI will guide you through the first five steps, then we will practice **brahmari** and observe a moment of **silence** in the body. You will need to produce a sound from the back of the throat during exhalation, similar to that of a bee or a bumblebee. This sound will rise into the cavity up to the **sinuses**, touching the entire brain area, including the tympanic cavity and the frontal, sphenoid, maxillary, and even temporal sinuses.\n\nWe will start by adopting an **upright position**. By keeping the back straight, exhalation will have a physiological **relaxing** effect on the **vagus nerve**, promoting the transition to the **parasympathetic recovery system**. If I hold myself poorly, I reduce this effect.\n\nI will experience this state of consciousness during inhalation. At the second level, I will pay very close attention to the act of breathing, aware of the body's movement. At the fourth level, I completely relax during exhalation, while remaining aware of my inhalation.\n\nWe will take **twelve breaths**. The first two will be done normally, and for the next ten, we will slightly block our ears. Inhale, then on exhalation, produce a small **humming sound**. Repeat this ten times, then release and enter the silence that settles. In this silence, allow a feeling of joy to emerge. If you don't know what to do, a simple **smile** may suffice.\n\nInhale again, exhale, and at the end of the exhalation, there is a space where you are not breathing. Place your mind in this space. Even when you inhale again, remain present in this space. By connecting to this perception, you get closer to **embryonic breathing**, which was not subject to diaphragmatic movement.\n\nYour heart began to beat after **21 days** of gestation. It is therefore beneficial to take a moment in this silence, because it is in silence that reorganisation can occur. This embryonic force is always present.\n\nTo get in touch with this presence, it is essential to accept going into silence. This can promote a **healing movement** and allow health to express itself more easily. By placing yourself in this silence, let the space open.\n\nIt is necessary to create this space, because without it, there is no development. This spacious silence allows the tissue to regain its ability to reorganise itself. The body knows how to reorganise itself when it is in this space, because it can use its innate **potential**. By giving this possibility back to the system, we allow it to regain its balance."
