        "cloudflareId": "9320f0f86a69f246100ef2d91ee2c99a",
        "duration": "09:49",
        "title": "24-Lung Development",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Lung Development\n\nThe development of the **lungs** can be considered a complex phenomenon related to embryonic growth. This process begins with the organisation of the **amniotic cavity** and the formation of the **foregut**, which includes the appearance of diverticula. As this evolution progresses, a pulmonary area takes shape, accompanied by the appearance of the **pulmonary orifices** and a suction field.\n\nDuring development, several movements occur. After a flexion movement, the embryo undergoes **lengthening** and **stretching**, followed by a straightening movement. This process is marked by a coiling that occurs between the 18th and 22nd day, with the closure of the **neural tube** and the anterior and posterior neuropores around the 28th day.\n\nAround the 26th day, a **laryngotracheal diverticulum** appears, as do the bronchial buds. This development is linked to a biodynamic suction process, where all glands form from epithelial tissue, whether **endodermal** or **ectodermal**. The lungs, originating from digestive-type tissue, begin to develop by forming the **main bronchi** from the trachea.\n\nIt is important to note that this development is a genetic response, but the environment plays a crucial role in stimulating the system. For example, a seed placed in an inappropriate environment will not germinate, while a seed in an adequate environment will flourish.\n\nAround the lungs, a **peritoneum**, a **visceral pleura**, and a **parietal pleura** form, enveloping the lung tissue. This mesodermal tissue, which is also extra-embryonic, plays an essential role in the suction field from the beginning of development.\n\nThe **diaphragm** originates neurologically at the third cervical vertebra. The phrenic nerve, initially very high, lengthens with the overall growth of the system. Parietal-type pains can radiate into the upper limbs, linked to this phrenic relationship, which can be interpreted as referred pain of sub-diaphragmatic origin.\n\nThe formation of the vertebral column and the densification of tissues are also key elements in this process. The **somatopleure** and the **splanchnopleure** play a role in tissue integration, contributing to the formation of the peritoneum and pleura.\n\nThe **pulmonary hilum** is a crucial space where the tissues of the visceral and parietal pleura meet. This space is simultaneously aerial, fluidic, lymphatic, and neurological, allowing gas exchange under partial pressure. During inspiration, the lungs perform a rotational and lengthening movement, facilitating gas exchange.\n\nIt is essential to understand that the lungs rely on a residual volume of air, allowing tilting movements during inspiration. The freedom of movement of the ribs and the endothoracic fascia is paramount to optimising lung function. Working on the lung in its suction phase helps restore its embryonic movement and improve its respiratory efficiency."
