        "cloudflareId": "65aec50bd0a87dd7b85f7845cb3d27ab",
        "duration": "05:35",
        "title": "26-Practice_The Lungs\n\n# The Lungs\n\n## Introduction\n\nThe lungs are two spongy, air-filled organs located on either side of the chest (thorax). The trachea (windpipe) conducts inhaled air into the lungs through its tubular branches, called bronchi. The bronchi then divide into smaller and smaller branches, the bronchioles, which end in tiny air sacs called alveoli.\n\n## Anatomy of the Lungs\n\n### Location and Structure\n\nThe lungs are located in the thoracic cavity, protected by the rib cage. Each lung is surrounded by a double-layered membrane called the pleura, which allows the lungs to slide smoothly against the chest wall during breathing.\n\n*   **Right Lung:** Larger and heavier, it is divided into three lobes (superior, middle, and inferior).\n*   **Left Lung:** Smaller, it is divided into two lobes (superior and inferior) to accommodate the heart.\n\n### Airways\n\n*   **Trachea:** The main airway, extending from the larynx to the bronchi.\n*   **Bronchi:** Two main bronchi (right and left) branch off the trachea and enter the lungs.\n*   **Bronchioles:** Smaller airways that branch off the bronchi.\n*   **Alveoli:** Tiny air sacs where gas exchange occurs.\n\n### Blood Supply\n\nThe lungs receive blood from two sources:\n\n*   **Pulmonary Arteries:** Carry deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs.\n*   **Bronchial Arteries:** Supply oxygenated blood to the lung tissue itself.\n\n## Function of the Lungs\n\nThe primary function of the lungs is to facilitate gas exchange between the air we breathe and our blood.\n\n### Respiration\n\nRespiration involves two main processes:\n\n1.  **Inhalation (Inspiration):** The diaphragm contracts and moves downwards, and the intercostal muscles contract, lifting the rib cage upwards and outwards. This increases the volume of the thoracic cavity, creating negative pressure that draws air into the lungs.\n2.  **Exhalation (Expiration):** The diaphragm relaxes and moves upwards, and the intercostal muscles relax, allowing the rib cage to move downwards and inwards. This decreases the volume of the thoracic cavity, creating positive pressure that forces air out of the lungs.\n\n### Gas Exchange\n\nGas exchange occurs in the alveoli. Oxygen from the inhaled air diffuses across the thin alveolar and capillary walls into the blood, while carbon dioxide from the blood diffuses into the alveoli to be exhaled.\n\n## Common Lung Diseases\n\n*   **Asthma:** A chronic inflammatory disease of the airways that causes episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing.\n*   **Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD):** A group of progressive lung diseases, including emphysema and chronic bronchitis, characterised by airflow obstruction.\n*   **Pneumonia:** An infection that inflames the air sacs in one or both lungs, which may fill with fluid or pus.\n*   **Lung Cancer:** Uncontrolled growth of abnormal cells in the lungs.\n*   **Cystic Fibrosis:** A genetic disorder that causes thick, sticky mucus to build up in the lungs, digestive tract, and other areas of the body.\n\n## Maintaining Lung Health\n\n*   **Avoid Smoking:** Smoking is the leading cause of preventable lung diseases.\n*   **Regular Exercise:** Helps strengthen the lungs and improve their capacity.\n*   **Avoid Exposure to Pollutants:** Minimise exposure to air pollution, chemicals, and allergens.\n*   **Vaccination:** Get vaccinated against respiratory infections like influenza and pneumonia.\n*   **Healthy Diet:** A balanced diet supports overall health, including lung health.\n\n> The lungs are vital organs that play a crucial role in our survival by ensuring the continuous supply of oxygen to the body and the removal of carbon dioxide. Understanding their anatomy and function is essential for appreciating their importance and taking steps to maintain their health.",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Lung Practice\n\nThe **posterior hand** is slightly lower than the **anterior hand**, which is slightly higher. This is due to the **rocking** movement of the lungs on their axis. This movement is essential for positioning oneself in the **embryonic field** of the lungs, where the **embryonic fulcrum point** is sought. This point represents a field of aspiration, allowing for repotentialisation in the primary function of the lungs, i.e., being ready to **take the breath of life**.\n\nDuring the nine months of embryonic development, the lungs are prepared for this first movement. They produce **amniotic fluid**, a crucial function as the embryo needs it for survival. This fluid partly originates from kidney urine. Later, a **specific protein** called **surfactant** will be produced, allowing the lungs to open at birth.\n\nInitially, the pressure applied is gentle. The aim is to gradually find a space where the lung can organise itself and regain its freedom. Between the **visceral pleura** and the **parietal pleura**, there is an interface between the trachea, bronchus, and the aerial bronchial tissue, which contains air and a residual volume, as well as a fluid space.\n\nIt is important to note that this tissue can harbour emotions, such as internalised **sadness**. For example, a child who \"cries in their lungs\" or suffers from bronchitis may be expressing a sadness they cannot verbalise. By gently working on this tissue, it is possible to initiate a dialogue and **tissue oxidative exchange**.\n\nThrough the **great posterior fissure**, one can access spaces where emotions are hidden. It is essential to let the body work and focus on the reorganisation axis. The **costopleuropulmonary recesses** are sacs for the accumulation of exudates, where lung waste is deposited. These areas, often less mobile, need to be energised and freed.\n\nIt is also crucial to free the lungs from their attachment points, particularly the **suspensory ligaments of the pleural dome**. The recesses, such as the **costodiaphragmatic recesses** and the **phrenomediastinal recess**, play an important role in the freedom of the mediastinum and the heart.\n\nAmniotic fluid production begins from the **fifth week** of pregnancy and develops until the **38th week**, with the appearance of surfactant around the **25th week**. Pulmonary pathologies, such as bronchitis or bronchiolitis, can be manifestations seeking to resolve unexpressed problems during the embryonic stage, manifesting as **fluid**. One could say that one \"cries in the lungs\"."
