        "title": "27- Meditation and Obstacles",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Meditation and Obstacles\n\nI am aware that I am breathing in, I am aware that I am breathing out. I become aware of my **breath** and my **body**. I relax my body and generate a feeling of **joy** and **happiness** in the present. I become aware of my **pain**, I embrace it and I take care of it.\n\nIt is important to have **good motivation** when you start meditating. Your mind will present you with **obstacles**. The first obstacle is **laziness**. This can manifest as **active laziness**, where you engage in many activities, except meditation. Another aspect of laziness is **giving up**, where you tell yourself that meditation is not for you after all. The antidote to this is to find **just motivation**, which should be not only for yourself, but also for others.\n\nThe second obstacle you will encounter is **forgetting** the methodology of meditation. At first, it is easy to get lost in your thoughts. I myself have experienced moments where I thought I was meditating, but I ended up daydreaming. Meditation is **mind training**, a discovery of how one's own mind works.\n\nIt is normal not to always feel good while meditating. The important thing is to learn to recognise and train your mind. The antidote here is **attention** and **mindfulness**. This allows you to discover the **energy** of your mind, **concentration**, which will gradually open you up to a **deep insight** into things.\n\nYou must progress gradually. Imagine entering a space where secrets are hidden behind the walls. You enter with a **candle**, which represents your mind. At first, the candle flame flickers, meaning there is no real brightness. However, through the practice of meditation, you learn to stabilise this flame. A luminous clarity then appears in your mind.\n\nThis clarity leads you to **deep insight**. It is essential to learn to stabilise your mind, as this requires **stabilisation** work. You must develop this clarity of mind through the energy of **mindfulness**, **concentration**, and **deep insight**. With practice, everyone can access this."
