        "duration": "03:13",
        "title": "28- Embryological Reconnection Reminder",
        "transcriptMarkdown": "# Embryological Reconnection Recall\n\nEach developing **organ** at every moment achieves the best of its **potential**. Each developmental stage can be considered a **function**. In an early stage, the **peritoneum** expressed an osmotic membrane, which could be considered a **primitive kidney**. In some cases, the peritoneum can revert to being a **dialysis membrane**.\n\nThe peritoneum, the **spleen**, and even certain parts of the **myocardium** can re-express **ontogenetic** adaptation situations and regain functions. The spleen is particularly important in the development of the **circulatory system**. During the establishment of this system, **pressures** are created in the spleen, influencing whether certain volumes open or not.\n\nFor a **vessel** to form, four components are necessary: a **trajectory**, a **metabolic concentration**, **vacuolations**, and the presence of **intercellular substances**. A vessel can be compared to a **rainbow**: in a given space-time, the presence of the sun, rain, and an adequate inclination are needed for it to appear. If one of these conditions disappears, the vessel also disappears.\n\nIn the **ontogenetic** process, vessels appear and then disappear, because there is a crucial **volumetric** balance between the heart, liver, spleen, and small intestine, which act as **blood sponges**, in collaboration with the **lungs**.\n\nAt the time of **birth**, there are not only bone compressions but also volumetric compressions. By compressing, blood flow increases in certain areas, thus modifying circulation patterns.\n\nSome people may be blocked at the spleen level, referred to as **splenic**. This can mentally manifest as **melancholic** tendencies. It is essential to release these pressure fields, as our mentality relies on volumes.\n\nWe learn in deep **silence**, often during **expiratory apnoea**. In this state, we continuously receive information. Similarly, in the tissue, we look for **points of silence**, as this is where the body reorganises itself.\n\nTrue silence is comparable to **gratitude**: it implies gratuitousness and freedom. This feeling of thankfulness is what the tissue seeks. It seeks to find its point of **gratitude** to rebalance itself. The embryo perfectly illustrates this process."
